


## HERSHKO SCHIMONOVICH MEEZOVICH HOFFMAN (HOCHMAN/HOYCHMAN/GONKHMAN)

![[bios/I39965497/img_hershel_hoffman.jpg]]
Born 8th February, 1888 in the village of Savran, Russia
Died Perth WA 11th December, 1969

Harry Hoffman (as he was known in Australia) was born 8th February, 1888  in in the village of Savran, Pedolia (nowadays PODILYA) Russia (Ukraine).

_From Mal Hoffman’s research (in 2005) SAVRAN ODES’KA, UKRAINE (Lat 48 degrees 08’ N Long 30 degrees 06’ E). Located approximately 50km NE of Balta and 100km from border of Moldova._

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Harry was the second son born to Shimon and Bracha.

From Nate Hoffman’s notes:
Harry’s parents fled Russia (as did Rachel’s) carrying Harry as a babe in arms during the Pogroms of the Czars time (Alexander III 1881 – 1894 or Nicholas II 1894 – 1917)

_Pogram: Russian term, originally meaning ‘riot’ that came to be applied to a series of violent attacks on Jews in Russia in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Pogroms were few before the assassination of Alexander II in 1881; after that, with the connivance of, or at least without hindrance from, the government, there were many pogroms throughout Russia. Soldiers and police often looked on without interfering. These pogroms encouraged the first emigration of Russian Jews to the United States. After 1882 there were few pogroms until 1903, when there was an extremely violent three-day pogrom at Chisinau resulting in the death of 45 Jews. Although it has not been conclusively proved that the Czarist government organised pogroms, the government’s anti-Semitic policies certainly encouraged them. After the abortive revolution of 1905, pogroms increased in number and violence. With the success of the Bolshevik Revolution, pogroms ceased in the Soviet Union; they were revived in Germany and Poland after Adolf Hilter attained power._

_See E.H. Judge, Easter in Kishinev: Anatomy of a Pogrom (1992) – Mal Hoffman._

They were taken to Rishon Le Zion. Both families dwelt there and raised their families.

**_Rishon Le Zain:_** _The fourth largest city in Palestine and 10 kilometers south and east of Tel Aviv Rishon Le Tzion, or the first of Zion, was founded in 1882 by a group of Russian settlers, and is credited with being the first modern agricultural settlement in Palestine (now known as Israel), hence the name._

Harry’s mother died when he was young. He had two siblings – Natri and Berl.

Following Bracha’s death, Shimon married Frieda Sisselman and they had five more children. (information received from Nate Hoffman)

From Nate’s notes Apparently Frieda didn’t like Harry and he ran away from home when he was about 11 years old. Shimon used some influence to get him a job working for a German engineering company that produced pumps and engines for wells. Harry trained as a fitter and turner.

He met the red-headed Rachel (Roochle/Rachelle) Gilik (Hilik) who had also been carried out of Russia as a babe in arms and the couple were married 18th April, 1908 in Jaffa, Palestine.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

From information given by Nate Hoffman during a conversation with Mal, Terry and Marie Hoffman in 2005, In 1914 the family moved to Egypt where Harry looked after an olive crushing plant (which could also grind wheat into flour).

Rachel did not like Egypt as the food market stalls were run by Arabs and hence food preparation was not “kosher” – a basic Jewish requirement.

Harry and Rachel had six children:

1. Boruch (Bruce):               10.04.1909 – 09.04.1981
2. Bentson/Benjamin (Ben): 01.05.1911 – 16.07.1976
Who were both born in Palestine,

3. A child was deceased and could have been born between 1911 and 1916

4. Nathan (Nate):                   28.02.1916
5. Rose:                                  2.3.1918 – 2.09.2005.
6. Nahimiah (Norm/Hammy) 17.02.1922 – 29.04.1971
7. Bella:                                 1925 - 7.09.1974 Perth WA
These four children were born in Perth Western Australia.

Harry and Rachel with sons Bruce aged 6 years and Ben aged 3 years came to Australia on board the Orient Line M V “Orsova” sailing from Port Said (on the Suez Canal in Egypt) on 28th May 1915. They paid Fifty-seven English pounds for their ticket which showed their name as Mr and Mrs Hochman. They arrived in Fremantle .

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

_Orient Line’s Orsova was built by John Brown & Co., of Glasgow. Launched in 1908, she made her maiden voyage from London to Melbourne, Sydney and Brisbane, via Suez, on 25th June 1909._

_She was converted into a troop transport in 1915. In 1917, while still serving as a trooper, she was torpedoed and badly damaged near Eddystone, with six deaths. She was beached and repaired survived the War and re-entered Orient Line’s Australian service in 1919. Orsova was scrapped in 1936._

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Harry age 33 years, Rachel age 33 years and the two boys Bruce age 13 years and Benjamin age 10 years were naturalized on 20th February, 1922. At this time their address was given as 31 Robinson Avenue, Perth Western Australia.

The certificate issued in Melbourne states Harry to be 33 years of age, 5 feet 4 inches tall, colour of eyes hazel, colour of hair dark brown and he had no special marks or peculiarities

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

On 23rd July, 1923 Harry, who was living at 1 Dangan Street, Perth, his occupation given as Engineer, paid f our hundred and eighty-five pounds to Sidney Pembroke Herbert for All that part or parcel of Land being portion of Lot 9 Perth Town Lot N.76 on deposited Plan 1287 and being the whole of the land comprised in Certificate of Title Volume 80 Folio 3.

Also: all that parcel of land being portion of Perth building lot N77 as delineated in the diagram and coloured green and numbered 5, on deposited Plan 547 and being the whole of the land contained in Certificate of Title Volume 49 Folio 274.

Also: All that parcel of land being portion of Perth Building Lot N77 and numbered 6 on deposited plan 547 and being the whole on the land comprised in Certificate of Title 45 folio 297.”

A deposit of Two hundred and fifty pounds was paid with the residue to be paid in consecutive quarterly payments of Fifteen pounds including interest at the rate of eight per cent p.a. quarterly rests, commencing on the first day of August 1923. Purchaser to have the right to pay off sums not less than ten pounds at any time in addition to above.

Harry purchased 74 Lincoln Street, Perth 29th August 1929 and owned it until 23rd August, 1971. (Both Harry and Rachel on 1931 Electoral Roll for East Perth at 74 Lincoln Street – Mal Hoffman research)

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

_Rachel in front of 74 Lincoln Street, Perth_

Harry was a fitter and turner and worked on various jobs around the Perth area.

Among his possessions are references from :

Abel Neumann Jaffa Palestine 31st December 1914.

Atlas Engineering Company Fremantle dated 7th March 1916. Harry had been employed by them for six months as a fitter and turner.

George Kent Ltd Railway Parade West Perth dated 18th September 1917 where he was employed from 13th March 1916 to 5th August 1917 as a fitter and turner.

Eilbeck Holding Pty Ltd, 2-20 John Street, Perth WA dated 20th December 1963 accepting with regret the retirement from the company after 46 years of continuous and meritorious service.

Harry worked with the Eilbeck family and retired after 46 years service at 73 years of age. He had been foreman for about 35 years – Mal Hoffman research)

Nate Hoffman, Harry’s third son who was born in Perth, wrote in his notes that  his father “was a brilliant engineer (Fitter and Turner) eventually becoming foreman of Eilbecks Engineering Works in West Perth where he worked for 43 years. They were the largest manufacturers of timber milling saws, nail making and woodworking machines in Western Australia. During Harry’s time there he worked on various projects including Government House Perth Gates or doors.  The nails were handmade.

Harry also worked at the New Norcia Monastery and Orphanage between Perth and Geraldton where olives were crushed for oil and Harry shared his knowledge of the crushing plant and improving its efficiency. The Monks were not able to pay any wages.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

_Harry and Rachel taken 16th August, 1955_

Harry and Rachel celebrated their 50th Wedding anniversary 18th April, 1958

Rachael died 8th May, 1964.

At the time of his death on 11th December 1969 at Maurice Zeffert Memorial Home, Yokine WA Harry had been in Australia for 54 years. He was 80 years old.

Harry died 11th December 1969

He was buried 12th December, 1969 in the Jewish area Karrakattta Cemetery Perth Western Australia.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

_The Machlin grave behind Harry’s is Leah Hoffman’s sister-in-law._

A further interesting comment from Mal Hoffman:

“The ticket for the ship’s passage from Port Said to Fremantle in May 1915 was issued for Mr and Mrs Hochman plus 1 child 6 and 1 child 3.

Hochman became Hoffman,

Boruch became Bruce, Bentson became Benjamin (which are the names shown on their death certificates)

The father Herchel became Harry (which is shown on his death certificate).

We’ll never know if this was a deliberate decision of Harry and Rachel to Anglicise their names to become more easily accepted in an ‘Énglish’ country or whether the clerk handling their immigration formalities (who may not have been a scholarly type) just wrote down the closest phonetic spelling he could get to what they said.

I have no record of dad ever being referred to as Bentson in Australia.”
